etymologies: late 16th century; earliest use found in George Turberville (c1543–c1597), poet and translator. From un- + penned

definitions: Not written with or as with a pen; not set down in writing.

etymologies: late 16th century; earliest use found in Wentworth Smith, playwright. Probably partly from unpen + -ed

definitions: Not shut up in a pen; unenclosed. Also occasionally: †that has been released from a pen (obsolete).
